WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:03.982
SPEAKER_00: In 1940, the Tacoma Narrows Bridge looked like the future.

00:00:04.863 --> 00:00:12.804
SPEAKER_00: It was long, slender, cheaper than the original conservative design, and beautiful enough to make its movement famous.

00:00:13.727 --> 00:00:16.554
SPEAKER_00: People called it Galloping Gertie.

00:00:17.344 --> 00:00:32.906
SPEAKER_00: the wind on collapse day was not extraordinary the bridge had already survived stronger autumn winds the hidden problem was what the bridge did to the air after it started moving its shallow solid plate girder deck was too flexible in torsion

00:00:32.887 --> 00:00:40.326
SPEAKER_00: Once the roadway began to twist, the motion changed the airflow, and the changed airflow fed the next twist.

00:00:41.329 --> 00:00:48.546
SPEAKER_00: Engineers were studying the motion, but the design culture had not yet made dynamic aerodynamic testing routine for bridges like this.

00:00:49.670 --> 00:00:51.173
SPEAKER_00: The bridge did not just meet wind.

00:00:52.036 --> 00:00:54.502
SPEAKER_00: It entered a behavior its own design made possible.

00:00:55.524 --> 00:00:56.366
SPEAKER_00: Small causes.

00:00:57.029 --> 00:00:58.792
SPEAKER_00: Massive consequences.
